542. Life Support Biosph Sci. 1997;4(1-2):55-9.

In vitro food production for isolated closed environments: formation of ripe 
tomato fruits from excised flower buds.

Applewhite PB(1), K-Sawhney R, Galston AW.

Collaborators: Galston AW(2).

Author information:
(1)Department of Biology, Yale University, New Haven, CT 06520, USA.
(2)Yale U, New Haven, CT

Excised preanthesis flower buds of young Pixie Hybrid tomato plants develop into 
red ripe fruits in aseptic culture on a modified Murashige-Skoog medium with 3% 
sucrose at pH 5.8. The addition of certain synthetic auxins (IAA, NAA, IBA), 
auxin precursors (ISA), or cytokinins (KIN, IPA, ZEA, BAP) to the medium 
improved the percentage of buds developing into fruits, the weight of the ripe 
fruits, or both. The best results were obtained by an auxin-cytokinin 
combination of 10 microM IBA with 1 microM BAP. Storage of the excised buds at 
low temperature (6 degrees C) for up to 4 weeks before transfer to 27 degrees C 
caused only minimal deterioration in size and number of the fruit crop. 
Extension of low-temperature storage to 8 weeks produced smaller fruits that 
took longer to develop. This system could produce fresh, ripe small tomatoes on 
a sustained basis for up to 2 months for an isolated environment such as a space 
vehicle or submarine.

