550. J Clin Invest. 2001 Sep;108(5):725-32. doi: 10.1172/JCI11909.

Cyclin D1 overexpression and p53 inactivation immortalize primary oral 
keratinocytes by a telomerase-independent mechanism.

Opitz OG(1), Suliman Y, Hahn WC, Harada H, Blum HE, Rustgi AK.

Author information:
(1)Division of Gastroenterology, University of Pennsylvania, Philadelphia, 
Pennsylvania, USA.

Comment in
    J Clin Invest. 2001 Sep;108(5):665-7.

The immortalization of human cells is a critical step in multistep 
carcinogenesis. Oral-esophageal carcinomas, a model system to investigate 
molecular mechanisms underlying squamous carcinogenesis, frequently involve 
cyclin D1 overexpression and inactivation of the p53 tumor suppressor. 
Therefore, our goal was to establish the functional role of cyclin D1 
overexpression and p53 inactivation in the immortalization of primary human oral 
squamous epithelial cells (keratinocytes) as an important step toward malignant 
transformation. Cyclin D1 overexpression alone was found to induce extension of 
the replicative life span of normal oral keratinocytes, whereas the combination 
of cyclin D1 overexpression and p53 inactivation led to their immortalization. 
This study also demonstrates that immortalization of oral keratinocytes can be 
independent of telomerase activation, involving an alternative pathway of 
telomere maintenance (ALT).

